Q1

  1. Plot the Quarterly Australian Beer production data ausbeer on any patterns you see?
beer2 <- window(ausbeer, start=1992)
autoplot(beer2)

  1. Look at the lag plot to make a decision about seasonal correlation. Comment. Also try decomposing the data and comment on the different components.
gglagplot(beer2, do.lines=FALSE, set.lags = c(12, 24, 36, 48))+ggtitle("Lag Plat for Australian Beer's Quarterly production")

#From the lagplots, we can see that there is a seasonal correlation between the quaterly plots where lagplot 1,5 and 9 have correlations and similarly 2 and 6, and lag 3 and 7, and lag 4 and 8
tt <- decompose(beer2)
plot(tt)

#The observed plot seems to be constant but when it is decomposed, we can see a clear down trend and seasonality in the decompostion of the data.
  1. Look at the acf plot and comment about stationarity.
acf(beer2)

#From the acf plots, we get many significant values due to which we can say that the acf plot is not stationary
  1. Difference and look at the acf plots. Comment.
df1 <- diff(beer2)
ggAcf(df1)

df2 <- diff(df1)
ggAcf(df2)

#From the 1st order differential and 2nd order differential, we can see a clear seasonality and dataset seems to be not stationary

beer2 %>% diff(lag=4) %>% diff() %>% ggAcf()

beer2 %>% diff(lag=4) %>% diff() %>% diff() %>% ggAcf()

#This model has a stationary ACF residual plot, almost normal Q-Q plot and significant p values for Ljung-Box statistics plot
  1. Compare your chosen model with a benchmark method.
fit=Arima(beer2,order=c(1,1,1),seasonal=c(1,1,1))
autoplot(beer2) +
  autolayer(meanf(beer2, h=12),
            series="Mean", PI=FALSE) +
  autolayer(naive(beer2, h=12),
            series="Nave", PI=FALSE) +
  autolayer(snaive(beer2, h=12),
            series="SNave", PI=FALSE)+
  autolayer(rwf(beer2, drift=TRUE, h=12),
            series="Drift", PI=FALSE)+
  autolayer(forecast(fit,12), 
            series="fit",PI=FALSE) +
  guides(colour=guide_legend(title="Forecast"))

#The fit is actually the perfect 'fit' when compared to other bench methods as it reciprocates the graph on seasonality
  1. Forecast for the next 3 years.
fit <- Arima(beer2, order=c(1,1,1), seasonal=c(1,1,1))
fit %>% forecast(h=12) %>% autoplot() #next 3 years

  1. Do a seasonal cross validation using 4 steps ahead forecasts.
